<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister `Concerned' Over U.S. Trade Law </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0803001594 Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 7 Mar 
94 p 2 </F>

<F P=103> PY0803001594 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Maria Helena Tachinardi in La Guaira, Venezuela] </F>
  [Text] Reacting to the U.S. decision to reinstate its Super 
301 trade law, Brazilian Foreign Minister Celso Amorim said: 
"We are concerned about the use of unilateral measures. The 
spirit behind the GATT Uruguay Round agreement is that all 
problems should be resolved multilaterally. One of the Uruguay 
Round's major achievements was the decision to strengthen the 
multilateral system as an advanced way of resolving 
controversies." On 4 March, Amorim held a working meeting with 
his Venezuelan counterpart, Angel Burelli Rivas, in La Guaira, a 
city located near Caracas, to negotiate the signing of an 
economic complementation agreement between their two countries. 
  Although Venezuela has no substantive trade problems with 
the 
United States -- as Burelli Rivas told GAZETA -- the Venezuelan 
press gave wide coverage to the new measure announced by 
President Bill Clinton. The Venezuelan media believe the Super 
301 will give Clinton special powers to pressure Japan into 
opening its market to U.S. products. 
  In the opinion of Burelli Rivas, the Super 301 could bring 
problems to the United States within the GATT Uruguay Round 
agreement. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

