<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Paul Admits FNCD Split; Urges Unity </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0803233394 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1130 
GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0803233394 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The appearance of contradictions within the National 
Front for Change and Democracy, FNCD, is normal, said 
Port-au-Prince Mayor Evans Paul during an interview with the 
information service of the Research and Action Center for 
Development [Centre de Recherches et d'Actions pour le 
Developpment, CRAD]. A copy of this interview reached the 
Haitian press agency. 
  After admitting that there has been a weakening of the front 
in the Chamber of Deputies, Paul asserted that dialogue could 
resolve the conflicts that have arisen within the front, to 
avoid social explosion [corrects himself] sorry, total 
explosion. He added that divergences within the FNCD are the 
product of circumstance, and could be easily resolved. In his 
opinion, the proposal voted as a resolution in the Lower Chamber 
must be analyzed and tailored to the stance expressed by 
President Aristide, whose views must be taken into account in 
order to reach a compromise. 
  Paul explained that FNCD's stance has not changed since 16 
February, when it rejected the appointment of a puppet prime 
minister. In conclusion, Paul invites all sectors to express 
unity so the solution to the crisis does not come exclusively 
from the United Nations or the four countries called, Friends of 
Haiti. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

