<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Retired Army Men Implicated in Bridge Attack </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0903020494 Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE in Spanish 8 Mar 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PA0903020494 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by PRENSA LIBRE special correspondent Henry </F>
Hernandez Marroquin] 
  [Text] Yesterday, Pablo Monsanto, commander of the 
Guatemalan National Revolutionary Unity (URNG), said that 
retired Generals Jose Luis Quilo Ayuso, Francisco Ortega 
Menaldo, and Roberto Perussina might be responsible for Sunday's 
dynamite attack on the San Juan River bridge, located at 
kilometer 20 on the Atlantic coast highway. 
  Monsanto denied that the URNG was responsible for the 
explosion, adding that the URNG has no men in the area and 
therefore could not participate in that terrorist attack. The 
rebel commander said that, in an attack of this type, one cannot 
rule out the participation of criminal groups who seek to stop 
the peace dialogue, and they might be linked to the retired 
military men who do not want to see an end to the 33 years of 
warlike conflict in Guatemala. 
  For a long time now, Monsanto added, the previously 
mentioned 
military men have caused divisions in the Army, and therefore, 
one cannot ignore their interest in the suspension of peace 
talks between the URNG and the government. Monsanto referred to 
the case of Quilo Ayuso, who during his farewell ceremony at the 
Polytechnic Institute pointed out there was division among the 
military forces. 

</TEXT>

