<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Union Leaders Take 100 Hostage, Demand Wage Hikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0803235294 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2048 GMT 8 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0803235294 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 8 Mar (NOTIMEX) -- Today, an 
official source reported that union leaders took hostage 
approximately 100 Quetzaltenango public office employees. The 
union leaders are demanding wage increases. The Quetzaltenango 
state employees warned they will only leave the offices when 
they are given the 40-percent wage increase they demanded from 
the government five weeks ago. 
  The National Police reported that approximately 800 
demonstrators held a protest and later seized the governor's 
headquarters and the Quetzaltenango municipality with more than 
100 employees. Public security authorities said police 
surveillance will be increased in the coming hours, and they 
will find a legal way to evacuate the municipality and the state 
governor's office. 
  Union leader Oswaldo Squich declared that public employees 
await the arrival of President Ramiro de Leon Carpio's 
representative to negotiate. The demonstrators coordinated 
their actions with the leaders of the National Federation of 
State Workers Unions, who are scheduled to meet with government 
representatives. 
  The government employees union leaders temporarily seized 
the 
National Palace, headquarters of the Guatemalan Government, a 
few days ago, over the same conflict. Monday, more than 30,000 
professors joined the protest movement. 

</TEXT>

