<F P=100> Colombia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Developments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0803193094 </F>
<F P=103> PA0803193094 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Colombian economic developments monitored through 8 
March. 
  EL TIEMPO has conducted a poll in Santa Fe de Bogota and 
Cali, determining "the cost of Colombians' basic basket 
increased approximately 3 percent during the first 20 days of 
February. This leads us to believe the increase will reach 3.5 
percent by the end of the month and that the accumulated 
increase for the first two months of the year could reach 6.7 
percent. This is a high and alarming rate, because the 
government expects to lull the cost of living increase at 19 
percent by the end of the year." The newspaper survey has also 
determined "meat, rice, coffee, lentils, and several fruits are 
mostly responsible for February's inflation." (Santa Fe de 
Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 28 Feb 94 pp 1a, 1b) 
  The National Administrative Department of Statistics (Dane) 
has reported the country's inflation rate amounted to 3.63 
percent in February, "the highest February rate in the last 10 
years." It has also reported "increased school tuitions and 
supplies and strong increases in the prices of certain produce 
prompted this month's increase in the cost of living." (Santa Fe 
de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 2 Mar 94 pp 1a, 1c, 3c) 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

