<F P=100> Eduador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Majority Wants Referendum on Reforms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA0803135594 Quito Voz de los Andes in Spanish 2300 GMT 7 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA0803135594 </F>
<F P=104>  Quito Voz de los Andes </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From "The Voz Andes Newscast"] </F>
  [Text] Two-thirds of the people in Quito and Guayaquil are 
in favor of the referendum convoked by the government on 
constitutional reforms. The Guayaquil daily EL UNIVERSO reports 
that out of 600 persons polled 63 percent said they agree with 
holding a referendum, while 37 percent said they are opposed to 
it. EL UNIVERSO adds that 66 percent do not know what the 
questions of the referendum are, while 34 percent do know what 
they are. 
  Other questions asked were whether congress should be a 
single chamber as it has been up to now or whether there should 
be two chambers. Another question was on the issue of double 
nationality for emigrants who have acquired another citizenship. 
  Ecuadoran President Sixto Duran-Ballen announced that on 1 
May there will be a referendum on eight questions that refer to 
elections, duration of deputies' terms, reelection for 
presidential and other public offices, and parliamentary control 
over state funds. 
  The referendum has been criticized by the majority of 
Ecuadoran political sectors, who say that it is unconstitutional 
and irrelevant. However, the poll discloses that the majority 
of people support the referendum. 
  The same poll states that 33 percent of people feel that the 
questions are very important; 34 percent say they are quite 
important; 27 percent describe the questions as not very 
important; while only 6 percent believe they are not important 
at all. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
