<F P=101> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Details, Conditions for New UN Sanctions Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL0903203194 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1145 
GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL0903203194 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The UN Security Council has given itself some time 
for reflection before adopting a draft resolution reinforcing 
the sanctions against Haiti in order to examine in detail the 
technical and political aspects of such a decision, indicated 
French Council President Jean-Bernard Merimee. It is a complex 
draft resolution and the Council needs some time to examine it, 
Mr. Merimee told the press after a Security Council consultative 
meeting attended by Dante Caputo. 
  It should be recalled that on 4 March, the group of four 
[France, Canada, Venezuela, and the United States] submitted to 
the Security Council, a resolution providing notably for the 
imposition of a trade embargo against Haiti and some sanctions 
against the military. 
  Those measures, which would be added to the oil and military 
embargo in effect since last year, would constitute a new 
attempt from the international community to force the Haitian 
military to give back power to President Aristide and to 
facilitate his return to Haiti. However, the resolution 
requires the effective cooperation of Mr. Aristide in the search 
for a political solution before the imposition of new sanctions 
against Haiti. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

