<H3> <TI>   Measures Adopted on Agricultural Transport </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1003024494 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1800 
GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1003024494 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In a meeting chaired by Candido Palmero Hernandez, 
first secretary of the Cuban Communist Party in Havana, and 
Agriculture Minister Alfredo Jordan Morales, special control and 
protection measures were adopted in Havana Province for the 1994 
Agro-94 [1994 agricultural harvest] campaign. 
  Approximately 1.5 million quintals of tubers and vegetables 
will be picked this month in Havana Province, including a 
significant quantity of potatoes, while in April some 2 million 
quintals of agricultural products are expected to be harvested. 
  These measures were adopted to prevent these agricultural 
products from reaching other destinations. These measures 
include the control of the fleet of trucks that will participate 
in the Agro-94 campaign, preventing them from taking other than 
assigned routes. These measures will not be limited to the 
outskirts of Havana, but will be extended to all of the 
capital's distribution and collection areas up to (La Placita). 
  During the meeting, Palmero Hernandez said that black market 
proliferation must be stopped. He added that certain elements 
are dedicated to profiting at the expense of the people. 

</TEXT>

