<H3> <TI>   Radio Reports UNHRC Approves U.S. Resolution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1003151294 Havana Radio Progreso Network in Spanish 1200 
GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1003151294 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Progreso Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The UN Human Rights Commission [UNHRC] has approved 
a resolution against Cuba that is in keeping with the 
traditional U.S. policy of hostility and reflects the constant 
politicization of that UN commission. The document presented by 
the United States was adopted by a vote of 24 in favor and nine 
against, with 20 abstentions. Nicaragua and El Salvador were the 
only Latin American countries to back the resolution. According 
to diplomatic sources, the result of the vote did not satisfy 
the United States which insisted, up to the last minute, that it 
would obtain 40 votes in favor. 
  A project similarly based on selectivity and discrimination 
in the treatment towards Cuba at the UN Human Rights Commission 
was also approved under U.S. pressure last year, by a vote of 27 
in favor -- only three more than this time. 

</TEXT>

