<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Center-Right, Center-Left Welcome Cardoso Candidacy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0803201394 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 6 
Mar 94 p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY0803201394 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Monica Dallari and Gilberto Nascimento] </F>
  [Text] Sao Paulo -- An anti-Lula [Luis Inacio Lula da 
Silva] has been found. Entrepreneurs and politicians from a 
broad variety of ideological sectors -- including those labeled 
center-right and center-left -- no longer doubt that Finance 
Minister Fernando Henrique Cardoso has the anti-Lula image 
today. Carlos Eduardo Moreira Ferreira, president of the 
all-powerful Sao Paulo State Federation of Industries (FIESP), 
has said: "His candidacy is perfectly viable. He is competent 
and enjoys credibility." 
  His supporters gleefully say that Cardoso's candidacy has a 
center-left profile and is the only one capable of dividing the 
left, attracting the center, and appealing to the right. Luiz 
Eulalio de Bueno Vidigal Filho, the director-superintendent of 
Cobrasma [Brazilian Railway Material Company] -- who is another 
business big-shot -- has said: "It will be great if he becomes a 
candidate. I will work hard for his nomination." 
  Cardoso's name is accepted by the elites who do not swallow 
the type of socialism imagined by PT [Workers Party] 
presidential candidate Luis Inacio Lula da Silva, who has led 
all the opinion polls with a 30 percent support for the past six 
months. 
  Entrepreneur Romeu Chap Chap, president of the Brazilian 
Association of Shopping Centers, says: "There is no question 
that he is the anti-Lula candidate," adding that a correct 
implementation of the economic plan "does not depend on him 
staying at the ministry." 
  Alvaro Augusto Vidigal, president of the Sao Paulo Stock 
Exchange (Bovespa), said: "Cardoso is the anti-Lula. He only 
needs to wait for his plan to be consolidated before leaving the 
government." Alcides Tapia, president of the Brazilian 
Federation of Banks (Febraban), has said that Lula and the PT 
are campaigning, and it is only natural for other groups to seek 
their own candidates. He added: "Minister Cardoso could be one 
of those candidates because he is prepared and has what is 
needed to fill the position." 
  Enthusiastic defenders of the anti-Lula candidacy think the 
minister has the basic ingredients to defeat the former Sao 
Bernardo do Campo workers leader. He has the image of a new 
politician, with credibility, experience, and a clean past. 
Lula has the same attributes, they admit, but lacks experience. 
  Other factors will also weigh in the balance when voters 
become polarized for an eventual runoff between Lula and Cardoso. 
  Gaudencio Torquato, a consultant in electoral campaigns and 
a 
Political Marketing professor at the University of Sao Paulo 
(USP), has said: "Brazilians want change but fear the jump is 
longer than they can manage unaided," adding: "Voters fear the 
unpredictability and ideas of Lula, which are considered 
revolutionary. Voters want change, but this is not the kind 
they want. In this field, Cardoso has the advantage." 
  In Torquato's analysis, Lula would be a clear favorite if 
the 
race becomes polarized against politicians like Paulo Maluf 
(PPR) [Progressive Renewal Party] or Orestes Quercia (PMDB) 
[Brazilian Democratic Movement Party]. As a political analyst, 
he dares to suggest that Fernando Henrique Cardoso's candidacy 
will be practically unbeatable in a runoff election against 
Lula. He forecasts that result: 70-30 in favor of Cardoso. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

