<F P=101> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Communications Satellites Subject to Final Tests </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0703214894 Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL in Portuguese 2 
Mar 94 p 12 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY0703214894 </F>
<F P=104>  Rio de Janeiro JORNAL DO BRASIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sao Paulo -- The National Institute of Space 
Research (INPE) already is testing Embratel's [Brazilian 
Telecommunications Company] communications satellite 
Brasilsat-B1, which should be launched in June. This will be 
the first of two satellites that will be part of the second 
generation of Embratel's communications satellites. 
Brasilsat-B1, which arrived in Sao Jose dos Campos on 28 
February, will be subject to final integration tests at INPE's 
Integration and Testing Laboratory (LIT) until the end of April. 
After being tested, the satellite will be transported to the 
Arianespace's Kourou launch in French Guyana, from where it will 
be transported into space by an Ariane rocket. 
  The tests at INPE, supervised by experts from INPE and 
Hughes 
Aircraft Co. -- a Los Angeles enterprise that built the 
satellite, will verify all the Brasilsat-B1 systems. 
<H5>  Second Generation </H5>
  The Brasilsat-B1 and B2 are the same type and look like the 
first-generation satellites--Brasilsat-A1 and A2, but are more 
advanced technologically and have better performance. The 
signals the new satellites send to earth are much more powerful. 
  The service life of the two satellites that will be 
replaced, 
Brasilsat-A1 and A2, estimated at eight to 10 years, is almost 
up. According to Embratel, their replacement will not affect the 
users, not even those who have parabolic antennas, who will 
continue to receive their television programs normally. The new 
satellites have an approximately 12-year service life, which 
means that Brazil's communications are guaranteed until the year 
2006. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

