<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arms Sales to Former Yugoslavia Denied </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY0903221194 Buenos Aires LA NACION in Spanish 9 Mar 94 p 
8--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> PY0903221194 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires LA NACION </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Answering a LA NACION inquiry on 8 March, Argentine 
Deputy Foreign Minister Fernando Petrella stated that the 
Foreign Ministry has taken no action leading to the sale of 
cannons and ammunition to the former Yugoslavia. 
  Petrella emphasized this statement by reminding the 
journalist that the United Nations has expressly banned the sale 
of arms to the currently conflict-torn former Yugoslavia. 
  According to the DYN news agency, the United Nations 
"thwarted a deal through which Argentina would sell arms to 
Liberia, although the shipment's final destination was to be one 
of the countries of the former Yugoslavia." 
  The DYN report added: "According to information on hand, the 
Foreign Ministry cleared the initial request and granted the 
appropriate approval for the deal. The Defense Ministry is no 
doubt involved as well." 
  According to DYN: "Official sources acknowledged only that 
Liberia was the intended destination of the arms and that the 
United Nations objected to the sale; however, the request for 
information that Radical Civic Union legislators submitted to 
Congress made it obvious that the deal had aroused strong 
suspicions." 
  Argentine Defense Minister Oscar Camilion told DYN it is 
impossible to sell arms to the former Yugoslavia because there 
is a UN embargo on such deals. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

