<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Movement for Integration of Women Launched </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1103001094 Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole in French 1700 
GMT 9 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1103001094 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Radio Metropole </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] In Port-au-Prince, a movement led by Attorney 
Mireille Durocher Bertin for the integration of Haitian Women, 
at a ceremony at the El Rancho Hotel, set as its objectives 
establishing a long chain of solidarity among Haitian women of 
all social classes. The organization aims for real integration 
of women into society, promotion of Haitian culture, returning 
self-confidence to women through specific programs to provide 
them access to health, education, and productivity. 
  The inauguration of the Movement for Integration of the 
Haitian Woman [Mouvement pour L'Integration de la Femme 
Haitienne] was marked by a reception at the El Rancho Hotel. On 
this occasion, presentations were made on the situation of women 
in Haiti, their role in the economy and in the family. 
  Researcher Gilbert Valme calls for a new social contract 
between the patriarchal and matriarchal systems, a way, 
according to Mr. Valme, of assuring a better future for Haitian 
children. Other speakers, engineer Ginette Mathurin and Attorney 
Mireille Durocher Bertin, spoke of the role of women in the 
economy, in the peasant environment, and of their legal status. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

