<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> Argentina </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radical Party Protests Training of Agents </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1003233294 Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD in English 10 
Mar 94 p 11 </F>

<F P=103> PY1003233294 </F>
<F P=104>  Buenos Aires BUENOS AIRES HERALD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] (DYN-NA) -- Radical Party deputies lodged a 
complaint in the Lower House yesterday to protest against the 
news that British secret services will be training Argentine 
agents in intelligence analysis. 
  The complaint was made known after city daily CLARIN 
published an article on Tuesday [8 March] saying that the 
agreement had been reached by SIDE [Secretariat for State 
Intelligence] state intelligence agency Secretary Hugo 
Anzorregui on a visit to Britain on Monday [7 March]. 
  A document signed by Deputy Antonio Berhongaray said that 
the 
deputies in question were both "surprised and disapproving" of 
the development especially given the recent history of conflict 
between Argentina and Britain. 
  They wrote that even if the service was essential it would 
have to pose no danger to "strategic policy and basic 
common-sense." 
  They added: "It seems obvious to the unaware mind that the 
training of personnel by foreign intelligence services enables 
the country carrying out the task to gain valuable insight into 
professional training and the makeup of the other country." 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

