<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Malan Discusses New Currency Implementation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1103013294 Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network in Portuguese 
2200 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1103013294 </F>
<F P=104>  Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The government will give at least six days notice 
before the launch of the new Brazilian currency, the real. 
  This was announced today in Belo Horizonte by Central Bank 
President Pedro Malan. 
  Malan said the decision on when to launch the real will 
depend on how widely the URV [Real Value Unit] is being used. 
Malan clearly stated that the change of currency will not take 
place before April. 
  [Begin Malan recording] We promise to give a few days notice 
before the launch of the real in order to give people time to 
settle matters regarding commercial papers with preestablished 
rates, post-dated checks, etc. [end recording] 
  Regarding an agreement with the IMF, Malan said it may be 
signed next week. He added that to safeguard the agreement, 
confirmation on the issuance of bonds to convert the Brazilian 
foreign debt has been postponed. 
  [Begin Malan recording] Brazil and the committee of banks 
have issued a communique addressed to the international 
financial community, which states that we still plan on 15 
April. This date will be confirmed late next week, around 18 
March. [end recording] 
  Pedro Malan confirmed that Minister Fernando Henrique 
Cardoso's economic plan, technically speaking, was approved by 
the IMF mission that visit Brazil recently. 

</TEXT>

