<F P=100> Brazil </F>
<H3> <TI>   Air Transportation Agreement Signed With Macau </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1103011294 Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL in Portuguese 4 Mar 
94 p 14 </F>

<F P=103> PY1103011294 </F>
<F P=104>  Sao Paulo GAZETA MERCANTIL </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Article by Jorge Freitas in Rio de Janeiro] </F>
  [Text] The Civil Aviation Department (DAC) on 3 March 
reported that Major Brigadier Renato Claudio Pereira, president 
of the Committee for Studies Related to International Air 
Navigation (CERNAI), on 1 March signed a bilateral air 
transportation agreement with Macau, the Chinese territory that 
will be administered by Portugal until 1999. 
  Signing the agreement for Macau was Jorge Ferreira 
Guimaraes, 
president of the Civil Aviation Authority. The agreement now 
will be reviewed by the Sino-Portuguese Liaison Group. 
  A DAC communique states that the agreement "is characterized 
by liberal operational provisions enabling the two parties to 
offer air services between Brazil and Macau to meet the needs 
for transportation of both passengers and cargo between the two 
parties, including those of third countries." 
  Macau is located on the southeastern coast of Asia, 64 km 
west of Hong Kong. The agreement will give Brazilian companies 
greater access to the Asian market. 

</TEXT>

