<F P=100> Suriname </F>
<H3> <TI>   Recovery Plan To Be Discussed in New York on 19 Mar </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1003150994 Rotterdam ALGEMEEN DAGBLAD in Dutch 10 Mar 94 p 
3 </F>

<F P=103> BR1003150994 </F>
<F P=104>  Rotterdam ALGEMEEN DAGBLAD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Pronk Wants To Talk To Suriname in </F>
New York"] 
  [Text] Paramaribo -- Cooperation and Development Minister 
Pronk has suggested to his Surinamese counterpart, R. Assen, 
that they talk about the Structural Adjustment Program (SAP) for 
the economy in New York on 19 March. 
  Paramaribo accepted the invitation and has approached the 
Warwick Research Institute (British university) to act as 
adviser. The International Monetary Fund (IMF) will be there 
for the Netherlands. 
  Pronk's invitation is a reaction to the Surinamese proposal 
of 24 February to begin talks as quickly as possible on a 
solution to the lingering question of external guidance for the 
SAP. In Paramaribo, emotions were running high this week 
following the sharp criticism levelled by Pronk at the 
Surinamese approach to the economic crisis. However, with the 
indignant statement made by Assen on the matter, the question 
would appear to be over. 
  The Netherlands is still demanding that Suriname takes on 
the 
IMF as an external adviser for the SAP before there can be any 
talk of resuming economic aid. However, Paramaribo wants to 
throw in its lot with Warwick. Warwick, however, only wants to 
give technical assistance and is "not prepared nor in a 
position" to coercively enforce the required measures, nor to 
advise The Hague on resuming aid. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-10719 </DOCNO>
