<F P=100> Chile </F>
<H3> <TI>   Warns Against `Sabotage' of Economic Plan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1103011094 Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network in Portuguese 
2200 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PY1103011094 </F>
<F P=104>  Brasilia Voz do Brasil Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Portuguese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Relay from Santiago, Chile, by Luiz Augusto Mendoca] </F>
  [Text] President Itamar Franco warned that those 
businessmen who try to sabotage the economic plan will be 
severely punished. 
  During a chat with journalists this evening, President 
Itamar 
Franco expressed his indignation over the price markups taking 
place throughout Brazil and asserted that the government must 
win the battle against price increases by any means. 
  Franco said that on 14 or 15 March the government will 
submit 
a draft bill to Congress containing very strict, severe 
sanctions on business people obstructing the economic plan. 
  The president, however, did not mention what type of 
sanctions the draft bill will contain. According to Franco, 
since Congress is also interested in doing away with constant 
price markups, he believes the draft bill might be approved 
expeditiously through an agreement with party leaders. 
  As for the abusive price increases, Franco asserted that 
talks with the business sector are not working, that the 
government holds talks democratically but despite these talks 
nothing happens, mentioning the pharmaceutical industry as an 
example. 
  Franco, who on 11 March will attend new Chilean President 
Eduardo Frei's inauguration, also talked about presidential 
succession and the rumor that Finance Minister Fernando Henrique 
Cardoso will be a candidate. Franco said Fernando Henrique 
Cardoso still has said absolutely nothing to him on whether or 
not he will be a candidate, and that it is up to him and his 
party, the PSDB [Brazilian Social Democracy Party], to decide 
but that he, the president, does not know what the minister has 
in mind. 
  President Franco added that if necessary the minister can 
make a decision in 24 hours but that he still has time because, 
after all, the deadline to resign in order to run for elections 
does not expire until 2 April, which means the minister still 
has 20 days to decide. 
  Franco ended by stating that the president of the Republic 
is 
responsible for choosing the finance minister and that Minister 
Cardoso, in his capacity as a democrat, would never suggest 
anybody for the post. 
  Franco also commented that Congress' decision not to extend 
the deadline for those holding a public post who want to run for 
elections to resign will speed up the succession process. 
  Soon President Franco will be leaving for La Moneda Palace, 
where he will have dinner with outgoing Chilean President 
Patricio Aylwin. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-10732 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat048_n_94007" </HT>


