<F P=100> Uruguay </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Economic Reports </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1103033194 </F>
<F P=103> PY1103033194 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
Article   Type:BFN 

  [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on economic activities in Uruguay monitored through 10 
March. 
  Despite the trade surplus in the last month of 1993, the 
1993 
trade balance deficit reached a record $679.1 million. This was 
the result of exports that totalled $1.6453 billion, a drop of 
3.4 percent, and imports of $2.3244 billion, an increase of 13.7 
percent. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 21 Feb 
94 Economic Page p 10) 
  The Central Bank reported that the value of fishing exports 
was $69.6 million in December 1993, a drop of 25.8 percent 
compared with the $93.8 million in the same month in 1992. 
(Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 22 Feb 94 
Maritime News Section p 1) 
  The export of nontraditional products increased 20.5 percent 
between 1989 and 1993. The items that registered a significant 
increase are: dairy products, 42.5 percent; lumber and 
furnitures, 166 percent; rubber products, 16 percent; machines 
and electrical appliances, 53.4 percent; and transportation 
material, 136 percent. The export of traditional products 
dropped 27 percent in the past four years. (Montevideo EL 
OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 24 Feb 94 p 8) 
  The National Ports Administration will invest a $2 million 
loan from the World Bank to finance projects in the port of 
Montevideo. (Montevideo EL OBSERVADOR ECONOMICO in Spanish 22 
Feb 94 Maritime News Section p 1) 

</TEXT>

