<F P=100> SOUTH AMERICA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Accord Signed To Strengthen Ties With Brazil </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PY1103211094 Madrid EFE in Spanish 1934 GMT 10 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PY1103211094 </F>
<F P=104>  Madrid EFE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Buenos Aires, 10 Mar (EFE) -- The Argentine and 
Brazilian foreign ministers, Celso Amorim and Guido Di Tella 
respectively, signed an agreement on 10 March on the need for 
regular meetings between the two countries aimed at 
strengthening their bilateral relations and stimulating the 
exchange of ideas and opinions. 
  Di Tella said that the agreement was signed after the two 
countries realized that Argentine-Brazilian bilateral relations 
were becoming too centered around Mercosur [Common Market of the 
South], that is, on talks centered around Mercosur concerns, 
while important bilateral aspects were being left aside. 
  The agreement was discussed last night, following a closed 
door meeting between representatives of the two countries to 
analyze Brazil's purchase of subsidized Canadian wheat. 
  Di Tella and Amorim also discussed the Argentine desire to 
have an option to join NAFTA, which is made up of the United 
States, Canada, and Mexico, without abandoning Mercosur. 
  The agreement establishes that the two countries' presidents 
will meet once a year, while representatives of all ministries 
and the foreign relations vice ministers will meet every three 
or four months. 
  Such meetings will create "ad hoc" working groups to discuss 
and follow specific matters. 
  Di Tella and Amorim announced the details of the agreement 
today, shortly before their meeting with the other Mercosur 
member countries' foreign and economy ministers. Mercosur is 
made up of Argentina, Brazil, Uruguay, and Paraguay. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

