<F P=100> CENTRAL AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> El Salvador </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cristiani: Peace Accords `Progressing Normally' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1203041694 San Salvador LA PRENSA GRAFICA in Spanish 10 
Mar 94 p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PA1203041694 </F>
<F P=104>  San Salvador LA PRENSA GRAFICA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] President Alfredo Cristiani yesterday said the peace 
accords are progressing normally -- in fact, some of them have 
been stepped up -- and only the total deployment of the National 
Civic Police (PNC), which is going along according to schedule, 
will be left pending by the time he concludes his term. 
  The president announced the government is about to present a 
plan to further expedite the land transfer program so it ends in 
May, when the new agricultural cycle begins. Cristiani 
explained the plan allows the possibility of issuing land 
appropriation titles with a specific value for each beneficiary 
-- whether he is a member of the FMLN [Farabundo Marti National 
Liberation Front] or the Armed Forces -- and they can personally 
expedite the negotiation with land owners who want to sell their 
assets. 
  The document can expedite the negotiation with land owners 
and the only remaining thing would be to sign a deed and grant 
financial aid through the Land Bank. The goal is to define the 
ownership of all the land, the president said. "Approximately 
10,000 FMLN members have received these benefits and 10,000 are 
still pending; while barely 2,000 Armed Forces members are still 
pending," he said. 
  Regarding the compensation demands from demobilized Armed 
Forces members, Cristiani said the government is complying with 
the peace accords' stipulations, and the protests are the result 
of a political movement. 
  The problem is that, in certain cases, persons show up and 
demand compensation even though they are not registered to 
obtain the benefits within a given period; and former fighters 
are demanding their inclusion, and this is not foreseen in the 
peace accords. "No country granted the necessary aid to pay the 
compensation, which surpass the 200-million-colones mark, so the 
funds come from the nation's general budget," he asserted. 
  Moreover, Defense Minister General Humberto Corado explained 
the Armed Forces are not trying to influence the 20 March 
electoral results; adding the corps' participation is 
constitutional and its work will be to place 14 helicopters at 
the disposal of the Supreme Electoral Tribunal [TSE] for the 
transfer of tally sheets from the most distant corners of the 
country. "The TSE said the tally sheets' transfer will be 
supervised by Onusal [UN Observers for El Salvador], the 
electoral boards, and the political parties," he emphasized. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-10760 </DOCNO>
