<F P=100> Guatemala </F>
<H3> <TI>   Army Spokeswoman Defends Civilian Patrols </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1103183194 Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE in Spanish 6 Mar 94 
p 3 </F>

<F P=103> PA1103183194 </F>
<F P=104>  Guatemala City PRENSA LIBRE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Army spokeswoman Edith Vargas de Marroquin stated 
that in spite of what has been said by Monica Pinto, a UN human 
rights expert, the armed institution believes that the voluntary 
Civilian Self-Defense Patrols [PAC] are positive for Guatemala. 
  Military reaction has come in the wake of a report prepared 
by Dr. Pinto that describes PAC's as the main violators of human 
rights in Guatemala and because the final resolution of the UN 
Human Rights Commission requested that PAC units in areas where 
there is no conflict be dissolved based on agreements that may 
be reached during the peace negotiations. 
  In noting that the Army's position is similar to that 
expressed by the Defense Ministry, Major Vargas affirmed that 
"the Army respects the position stated by the UN representative 
but we have our own opinion." She suggested that next time the 
UN expert visits Guatemala, "she should stay longer because this 
would permit her to speak with all the sectors, including PAC 
members." The major said that a longer visit would allow Dr. 
Pinto to have a broader idea and learn about special cases that 
cannot be understood in only eight days. 

</TEXT>

