<H3> <TI>   Troops Said To Thwart 2 Coup Attempts </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1203213094 Panama City ACAN in Spanish 1812 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA1203213094 </F>
<F P=104>  Panama City ACAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Guatemala City, 12 Mar (ACAN-EFE) -- Troops loyal to 
Guatemalan President Ramiro de Leon Carpio have thwarted two 
coup attempts against his government over the past three months, 
the Guatemalan newspaper EL GRAFICO reports today. 
  The newspaper, which cites Army "officers" as its sources, 
reports de Leon has been the object of two thwarted coups since 
he assumed the Presidency in June 1993, replacing deposed 
President Jorge Serrano, following his self-perpetrated coup on 
25 May of the same year. 
  Troops loyal to the president thwarted the attempted coups, 
the paper reported without expanding on the details of those who 
participated in the alleged coups to disrupt constitutional 
order. 
  The report adds after the thwarted coups the Army "has been 
strengthened, and democracy is safe." 
  Both de Leon and his defense minister, General Mario Rene 
Enriquez, have denied intense rumors of alleged coup attempts to 
unseat the chief of state. 
  They have admitted, however, "retired military and 
frustrated 
politicians," who were not identified, once knocked on the doors 
of the garrisons to promote a coup d'etat against Ramiro de 
Leon, former human rights ombudsman. 
  Enrique states the Armed Forces will no longer lend itself 
to 
any more revolts as in the past and that institutionality and 
the democratic process are guaranteed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

