<F P=101> Cuba </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Wants U.S. Telecommunications Links </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PA1303030094 Havana Radio Havana Cuba in Spanish 0000 GMT 13 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> PA1303030094 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Havana Cuba </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Evening Information Review" newscast] </F>
  [Text] Cuba has reiterated its willingness to restore 
telephone communications with the United States through 
agreements with U.S. telecommunications companies that are able 
to follow the proper procedures justly, equally, and reasonably. 
An official note from the Cuban Government states it is 
awaiting a decision from the U.S. Federal Communications 
Commission, which could authorize three of that country's 
companies to initiate telecommunication services to Cuba. 
  The information, reported by the official newspaper GRANMA, 
says these are norms established by the State Department for 
U.S. long-distance telephone companies. The note specifies 
Havana-based EntelCuba [National Telecommunication Enterprise of 
Cuba] signed recently separate agreements with three U.S. 
companies from Washington, Oklahoma, and Mississippi. GRANMA 
has reported the parties have agreed to establish a distribution 
rate of $1.20 per minute, divided by 50 percent between the 
Cuban and U.S. companies. 
  The note explains before 1991, when Hurricane Andrew 
interrupted telecommunications between the two countries, Cuba 
paid, for humanitarian reasons, all costs of the service, which 
originated in Cuban territory, without receiving a single cent 
of what was legally and justly its share. It explains that 
since 1966, as a result of the blockade, there have been 
accounts in U.S. banks totaling $100 million, resulting from 
operations various governments have carried out to prevent the 
telephone company from paying Cuba. 
  Negotiations between EntelCuba and the U.S. companies began 
during the second half of 1993, after the current U.S. 
Government authorized the resumption of traffic and the payment 
of Cuban telephone services. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-10766 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drlat049_a_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-LAT-94-049 </AU>
