<H3> <TI>   Ambassador Denies Colombian Rebels Met in Cuba </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1103203794 Havana Radio Rebelde Network in Spanish 1800 
GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1103203794 </F>
<F P=104>  Havana Radio Rebelde Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Spanish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Today, in Bogota, Cuban Ambassador to Colombia Jesus 
Martinez reiterated that a meeting of Colombian rebel leaders 
never took place in Cuba. In an interview with the Radio Caracol 
network, due to the insistence of the EL TIEMPO newspaper that 
such a meeting took place, the Cuban diplomat stated that they 
are being fooled by someone interested in destroying the 
excellent relations between the two countries. Those accusations 
were also denied by the Colombian Government and the minister of 
defense, as well as by several of the participants in a 
solidarity meeting held in Havana in January. 
  The Communist Party of Colombia, as an organization that 
participated in the forum that was held in Havana, issued a 
statement saying that any attempt to distort the nature of the 
Latin American meeting was an effort to reaffirm the infamous 
U.S. blockade against Cuba. The note also stated that efforts 
are being made to block the sale of oil to Cuba, a transaction 
that was recently approved by the Colombian Government and 
condemned by recalcitrant minority groups of Cuban emigres in 
Miami. 

</TEXT>

