<F P=100> Haiti </F>
<H3> <TI>   Deputy Blames U.S. State Department </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  FL1103222394 Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio in French 1130 
GMT 11 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> FL1103222394 </F>
<F P=104>  Port-au-Prince Signal FM Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In reaction to the parliamentary plan approved by 
the lower chamber, National Front for Change and Democracy 
Parliamentary Bloc [BP-FNCD] President, Deputy Fignole 
Jean-Louis, says this plan was developed at the initiative of 
the U.S. State Department. He holds the U.S. Government 
responsible for the current situation in the country: 
  [Begin Jean-Louis recording, in Creole] All the actions 
being 
taken by my colleagues, including deputies and senators, have 
been dictated by the State Department. We know this very well. 
The State Department has already forced the parliament, 
including deputies, senators, and the president, to take a 
number of measures such as -- you recall -- the Washington 
agreement. These same men had the president sign it, and got the 
parliament involved. Once we arrived here, they gave us no 
support for voting on the agreement, which could have ended the 
crisis. 
  Second, they had us go to Governors Island, then in an 
underhanded manner, sabotaged the Governors Island Agreement. 
Consequently, it could not be implemented. They had us 
participate in the New York pact for the normalization of 
parliament, then encouraged the 18 January parliamentarians to 
create all the disturbances you now see going on. You know what 
happened in the Senate on 9 March. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

